  "summary": "Inspector Spence visits David Hunter and Rosaline Claude to investigate the murder of a man at the Stagg Inn. The victim, who used the name Enoch Yates, had his head bashed in. Spence reveals that Yates claimed to be a friend of the late Robert Anderson (also referred to as Robert André or Robert Andhay) and suggested that Anderson was still alive. David, maintaining a calm and defensive demeanor, dismisses these claims as a hoax and asserts that Robert was his sister's first husband who died of blackwater fever in Africa.\n\nWhen Spence questions David about his whereabouts between seven and eleven the previous night, David refuses to answer, citing a dislike of being coerced. Spence warns him that he will be called for formal questioning. To advance the investigation, Spence requests that Rosaline identify the body, noting that a witness heard the deceased mention Robert. Surprisingly, Rosaline agrees to go. David supports her decision, and Spence arranges for a Daimler rental car to transport them.\n\nOn the way to the morgue, Rosaline is visibly terrified and pale. She whispers to the sergeant that she is fearful due to a past trauma in London where everyone in her house died during an air raid, leaving her as the sole survivor. David encourages her to be brave, telling her the deceased will look peaceful.",
